Lemmatization¶

In [199]:
# Importing the lemmatization module within nltk
from nltk.stem import WordNetLemmatizer

lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()

# tokenizing each row 
data['words_tweet'] = data['clean_tweet'].apply(word_tokenize)

data['lemmatized_words'] = data['words_tweet'].apply(lambda x: [lemmatizer.lemmatize(word, pos='a') for word in x]) 
# a denotes adjective in "pos"
# for loop is used -  to lemmatize each word inside every tweet

# Importing SentimentIntensityAnalyzer 
from vaderSentiment.vaderSentiment import SentimentIntensityAnalyzer
sentiment = SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()

# performs sentiment analysis using the polarity scores
# lambda function takes the list of lemmatized words in each row (x) and joins them to form a single string
# Range of negative scores: 0.0 to 1.0  - the score is the probability of the word being negative
# Range of positive scores: 0.0 to 1.0  - the score is the probability of the word being positive

data['sentiment_scores'] = data['lemmatized_words'].apply(lambda x: sentiment.polarity_scores(' '.join(x)))

Running Models on your cleaned dataset

Splitting Our Data Into Train and Test Subsets¶

In [218]:
# importing train_test_split
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

# X variable represents the input or features of the model
X = data['clean_tweet']

# y variable label or target variable for sentiment associated with each tweet 
y = data['sentiment_scores']
 
# we are splitting the train & test data in 90% and 10% respectively
# here random set is just a seed value which helps in setting a fixed random data for reproducibility
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X,y,test_size = 0.10, random_state = 777)

Transforming the Dataset Using TF-IDF Vectorizer¶

In [ ]:
print('''
During the fitting process, the TF-IDF Vectorizer learns the vocabulary from the training data and computes the IDF values for
each term  in the corpus. It also assigns a unique index to each term in the vocabulary.
''')
In [219]:
# Importing necessary libraries
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfVectorizer
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix, classification_report

# initializing the TF-IDF Vectorizer
vectorizer = TfidfVectorizer()

# Fitting and transforming the training data into TF-IDF vectors
X_train_tfidf = vectorizer.fit_transform(X_train)

# Transforming the test data using the trained vectorizer
X_test_tfidf = vectorizer.transform(X_test)
In [220]:
# Convert labels to binary format
y_train_binary = [1 if label['compound'] >= 0 else 0 for label in y_train]
y_test_binary = [1 if label['compound'] >= 0 else 0 for label in y_test]

from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, confusion_matrix
import numpy as np
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Instantiate the Logistic Regression model
logistic_regression_model = LogisticRegression()

# Fit the model on the training data
logistic_regression_model.fit(X_train_tfidf, y_train_binary)

# Make predictions on the test data
y_pred3 = logistic_regression_model.predict(X_test_tfidf)

# Calculate the accuracy of the model
accuracy = logistic_regression_model.score(X_test_tfidf, y_test_binary)

# Generate the classification report
classification_report = classification_report(y_test_binary, y_pred3)

# Create the confusion matrix
cf_matrix3 = confusion_matrix(y_test_binary, y_pred3)

# Print the accuracy and classification report
print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy}")
print("\nClassification Report:\n", classification_report)

# Set the categories for the heatmap
categories = ['Negative', 'Positive']

# Define the group names for the confusion matrix
group_names = ['True Neg', 'False Pos', 'False Neg', 'True Pos']

# Calculate the percentages for each group in the confusion matrix
group_percentages = ['{0:.2%}'.format(value) for value in cf_matrix3.flatten() / np.sum(cf_matrix3)]

# Create the labels for the heatmap
labels = [f'{v1}\n{v2}' for v1, v2 in zip(group_names, group_percentages)]
labels = np.asarray(labels).reshape(2, 2)

# Plot the confusion matrix as a heatmap
sns.heatmap(cf_matrix3, annot=labels, cmap='Blues', fmt='', xticklabels=categories, yticklabels=categories)

# Set the labels and title for the heatmap
plt.xlabel("Predicted values", fontdict={'size': 14}, labelpad=10)
plt.ylabel("Actual values", fontdict={'size': 14}, labelpad=10)
plt.title("Confusion Matrix", fontdict={'size': 18}, pad=20)

Which Model Can We Use¶

In [279]:
print('''
Both SVM and Logistic Regression show higher accuracy scores compared to Bernoulli Naive Bayes. 
Additionally, all models have relatively high precision, recall, and F1-scores for both classes.
Considering the overall performance, the SVM and Logistic Regression models are quite similar. 

However, SVM performs slightly better in terms of accuracy, precision, and F1-score for class 0. It also has a higher recall for class 1. 
ROC curve (area)=0.91 -- for SVM
ROC curve (area)=0.90 -- for LR

Therefore, based on these metrics, we can conclude that the SVM model is the best choice for this use case. ''')

Both SVM and Logistic Regression show higher accuracy scores compared to Bernoulli Naive Bayes.

Therefore, based on these metrics, we can conclude that the SVM model is the best choice for this use case.
